In [[Computational complexity theory|computational complexity]], the '''logarithmic time hierarchy''' ('''LH''') is the [[complexity class]] of all [[computational problem]]s solvable in a [[Logarithmic growth|logarithmic]] amount of [[computation time]] on an [[alternating Turing machine]] with a bounded number of alternations. It is a special case of the hierarchy of [[Alternating_Turing_machine#Bounded_alternation|bounded alternating Turing machine]]s. It is equal to [[FO (complexity)|FO]] and to FO-uniform [[AC0]].<ref>{{cite book | author=N. Immerman | title=Descriptive complexity | date=1999 | publisher=Springer | page=85}}</ref> 

The <math>i</math>th level of the logarithmic time hierarchy is the set of languages recognised by alternating Turing machines in logarithmic time with [[Random-access Turing machine|random access]] and <math>i-1</math> alternations, beginning with an [[existential state]]. '''LH''' is the union of all levels.

